<p><i><b>God is not Great: How Religion Poisons Everything</b></i> <a href="/wiki/2007_in_literature" title="2007 in literature">(2007)</a> is a book-length <a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_religion" title="Criticism of religion">critique of religion</a> by author and journalist <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Hitchens" title="Christopher Hitchens">Christopher Hitchens</a>. It was published in the United Kingdom as <i><b>God is Not Great: The Case Against Religion.</b></i></p>
<p>In the book, Hitchens contends that religion is "violent, irrational, intolerant, allied to <a href="/wiki/Racism" title="Racism">racism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tribalism" title="Tribalism">tribalism</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Bigotry" title="Bigotry">bigotry</a>, invested in <a href="/wiki/Ignorance" title="Ignorance">ignorance</a> and hostile to <a href="/wiki/Freethought" title="Freethought">free inquiry</a>, contemptuous of women and <a href="/wiki/Coercion" title="Coercion">coercive</a> toward children." Hitchens supports his position with a mixture of personal stories, documented historical anecdotes and critical analysis of religious texts. His commentary focuses mainly on the <a href="/wiki/Abrahamic_religion" title="Abrahamic religion" class="mw-redirect">Abrahamic religions</a>, although he also touches on other religions such as <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hinduism</a> and <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a>.</p>
